Kung Fu Panda 3
7.2
AdvertisementBy NEIL GENZLINGER“What we didn’t know was which A-list actor would be recruited to provide the voice of this father. What star could the producers get who would match the other household names — Dustin Hoffman, Angelina Jolie, Lucy Liu and more — routinely attracted by this franchise?The answer turns out to be The Times critic Neil Genzlinger reviews “Kung Fu Panda 3.”That gives His quest becomes a journey to find his inner panda and leads him to all sorts of realizations. The overriding one, which sounds tailored to the age of nontraditional families, is that he can make room for two dads in his life, his biological one and the goose who raised him, Mr. Ping. Po has to confront some fairly grown-up ideas in this installment — the character has certainly matured over the three films. But lots of comedic fight scenes break up the story’s more somber stretches, and the animation, especially in 3-D, is simply gorgeous. The kiddies might not appreciate the artistry, but grown-ups certainly will.Advertisement“Kung Fu Panda 3” is rated PG (Parental guidance suggested) because kung fu can get pretty rough. Running time: 1 hour 35 minutes.





